In this method, the effect of CDs on different plants has been investigated. In this approach, the interaction of CDs with plants is in various forms, such as soil cultivation, hydroponic cultivation, foliar feeding, and light-harvesting film, which are explained in the following subsections. Concerning the soil and hydroponic cultivation of CDs, the question arises of whether CDs can penetrate the roots and reach the photosynthetic parts through the vascular system. In a study by Kuo et al., this process has been well investigated. They showed that the CDs applied hydroponically on two lettuce and tomato plants are readily absorbed by these plants and accumulate in the roots and aerial organs. In their study, fluorescence microscopy was used to accurately track the penetration process due to the optical properties of CDs, and electron microscopy was also applied to demonstrate the presence of CDs in different organs (
                        Fig. 4

                        ) [107]. In fact, because of their small size (less than 10 nm), CDs can easily pass through barriers and penetrate plant tissues. Some studies of plant cultivation by soil and hydroponic methods showed that CDs usually penetrate the roots in the first step and move towards the stems and leaves in the following stages [54,108–110].

The explanation of hydroponics includes any system that allows plants to grow without soil. Water and minerals were carried out with or without a growing medium, such as stone wool, peat, perlite, pumice, etc. [111]. In recent years, CDs have been added to the nutrient solution to investigate their effect on plant growth. Based on a recent study, the fabricated CDs that can convert the longer wavelengths of UV light to far-red emission (625–800 nm) can be absorbed and utilized by Roman lettuce chloroplast. The absorbed CDs extend the chloroplast's solar energy spectrum and consequently enhance Roman lettuce's photosynthetic activity, as confirmed via both in vivo and in vitro results. Due to the increase in electron transfer efficiency between PSII to PSI, the in vitro coated chloroplasts with CDs show a higher adenosine triphosphate (ATP) production rate. These results were confirmed by in vivo studies of the Roman lettuce. In comparison with the control group, the lettuce plants treated with CDs exposed 28% higher electron transfer rate and 51.1 and 24.6% enhancement of fresh and dry weights, respectively (
                           Fig. 6a, b
                           ) [87]. Based on another study, the conjugated CDs with chloroplast can convert useless UV radiation (300–370 nm) to active photosynthetic radiation (370–500 nm) without energy transfer to the chloroplasts. This mechanism of growth increasing in plants is examined in rice plants as a real sample [112].

Despite various reports on CDs and other up-converting nanoparticles (UCNPs), there is no real example of these products in agriculture [122–124]. The UCNP@CDs can simultaneously convert NIR and UV photons in sunlight to visible light, which increases photosynthesis in living plants by 12% [125]. In addition to converting the yellowish-green light to red light, the proposed CDs/PVA film exhibit sufficient hydrophobicity, environmental friendliness, and antioxidant capacity (
                           Fig. 8a
                           ). According to the results, using CD/PVA antioxidant film enhanced the photosynthesis process in the mung bean as the real sample, which increased biomass and chlorophyll content (Fig. 8b–d) [126].

Photosynthesis is a vital pathway in plants to harvest chemical energy from solar light [127,128]. The complicated biological PSI and PSII in chloroplast organelles are responsible for this amazing energy conversion [129]. The chlorophylls a and b (light-absorbing agents in the chloroplast) can only absorb the visible region of the light spectrum (400–700 nm), consisting of blue to red light. Violet and orange light are mostly absorbed via chlorophyll a, while blue and yellow light is mostly absorbed by chlorophyll b. In addition, both also absorb light at other wavelengths with less intensity. Therefore, most research is focused on developing new light-harvesting systems that can absorb more solar energy in the visible part of the light spectrum or a more comprehensive range of wavelengths. A meaningful way to increase the effectiveness of chloroplasts in capturing sunlight is to create hybrid systems using chloroplasts and CDs. Absorption of light at invisible wavelengths by CDs is helpful because it emits light at visible wavelengths that can be used by chlorophyll a and b. This means that the ability of chloroplasts to absorb light increases and enhances the photosynthetic efficiency of plants [105]. Li et al. examined light-harvesting CDs to increase the biological photosynthesis of chloroplasts. After the assembly of CDs and chloroplasts, composite materials' adsorption in the spectrum's UV region becomes stronger (
                        Fig. 10a
                        ) and increases photosynthetic activity [59]. In spite of reliable outcomes in the hybridization of chloroplast with fluorescent emissive materials, there are significant challenges that need more investigation. At first, most light-harvesting materials can only convert UV light to visible light. The short lifetime of fluorophores in the excited state is the other obstacle that decreases the chance of energy transferring between light-harvesting materials and chloroplasts. Consequently, investigation of new advanced light-harvesting materials with long excitation lifetimes and good absorption in the UV, red, and NIR regions is necessary for improving energy harvesting by plants.

Nowadays, the greenhouse creates significant environmental concerns for scientists. The release of CO2 into the atmosphere produced by fossil fuel consumption is responsible for this hazardous effect. Rationally, reconversion of produced CO2 to its hydrocarbon sources can effectively solve this problem [151]. In addition to developing jungles and woodlands, manufacturing artificial photosynthetic agents can help decrease atmospheric CO2. By coupling water splitting and CO2 reduction, the artificial leaves can remarkably mimic the natural photosynthesis process without requiring an external electron donor [152]. If their high cost, high-energy consumption, and low selectivity are resolved, noble metals can be used as a catalyzer for this reaction [75]. As another efficient way, CDs can be used as a powerful photocatalytic catalyst due to their wide light absorbance, fluorescence properties, and electron transfer ability (
                        Fig. 12

                        ). Reducing CO2 molecules to the CO, CH4 and other hydrocarbons is the common way to remove this gas from the atmosphere. The PEGylated CDs coated with Pt or Au as photocatalysts are introduced as a unique technique for converting CO2 gas to formic acid at room temperature. To turn the formic acid into sodium formate, the formic acid was created through distillation, gathered, and basified to pH 12 with NaOH solution [153].

1) As mentioned, CDs can absorb ultra violet light that plants cannot absorb and convert it into longer wavelengths that plants can employ to accelerate their photosynthetic process. However, most prepared CDs have been reported in this field exhibit blue emission (
                        Table 1
                        ). Therefore, there is a need to conduct more studies using CDs with red emissions to extend the light spectrum that is available for plant consumption.
